Empirical Comparison of Classification Algorithms

An empirical study in the style of Caruana & Niculescu-Mizil (2006)

This notebook systematically compares multiple classification algorithms across diverse datasets with varying training set sizes to understand their relative performance and generalization behavior.

    # Number of samples
    n_samples = X.shape[0]
    print(f"\n Number of samples: {n_samples:,}")
    
    # Number of features
    n_features = X.shape[1]
    print(f" Number of features: {n_features}")
    
    # Feature types breakdown
    numeric_features = X.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).columns.tolist()
    categorical_features = X.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'bool']).columns.tolist()
    
    print(f"   - Numeric features: {len(numeric_features)}")
    print(f"   - Categorical features: {len(categorical_features)}")
    
    # Missing values
    missing_counts = X.isnull().sum()
    total_missing = missing_counts.sum()
    
    if total_missing > 0:
        print(f"\n Missing values: {total_missing:,} total")
        print("   Features with missing values:")
        for col, count in missing_counts[missing_counts > 0].items():
            pct = (count / n_samples) * 100
            print(f"     - {col}: {count:,} ({pct:.2f}%)")
    else:
        print(f"\nMissing values: None")
    
    # Class distribution
    target_col = y.columns[0]
    class_counts = y[target_col].value_counts().sort_index()
    
    print(f"\nTarget variable: '{target_col}'")
    print(f"   Class distribution:")
    for class_label, count in class_counts.items():
        pct = (count / n_samples) * 100
        print(f"     - {class_label}: {count:,} ({pct:.2f}%)")
    
    # Class balance check
    max_class_pct = (class_counts.max() / n_samples) * 100
    if max_class_pct > 70:
        print(f"    Imbalanced dataset (majority class: {max_class_pct:.1f}%)")
    else:
        print(f"   Relatively balanced dataset")

# Figure 3: Scale Differences in Numerical Features

dataset_colors = ['#3498db', '#e74c3c', '#2ecc71', '#f39c12']

fig3, axes3 = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(14, 10))
axes3 = axes3.flatten()

for idx, (dataset_name, (X, y)) in enumerate(datasets.items()):
    ax = axes3[idx]
    
    # Select only numerical columns
    numeric_cols = X.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).columns.tolist()
    
    if len(numeric_cols) > 0:
        # Prepare data for boxplot (handle NaN values)
        numeric_data = X[numeric_cols].values
        
        # Create boxplot
        bp = ax.boxplot(numeric_data, 
                        patch_artist=True,
                        boxprops=dict(facecolor=dataset_colors[idx], alpha=0.6),
                        medianprops=dict(color='red', linewidth=2),
                        whiskerprops=dict(color='black', linewidth=1),
                        capprops=dict(color='black', linewidth=1),
                        flierprops=dict(marker='o', markerfacecolor='red',

    else:
        ax.text(0.5, 0.5, 'No numerical features', 
                ha='center', va='center', fontsize=12, transform=ax.transAxes)
        ax.set_title(dataset_name, fontsize=11, fontweight='bold')

 Feature scale analysis complete
   Large scale differences require StandardScaler
   Critical for distance-based (KNN, SVM) and gradient-based (LR) algorithms

Figure Interpretation:

This boxplot visualization reveals the scale differences across numerical features within each dataset:

  • Extreme range variations: Features span vastly different magnitudes (some in single digits, others in thousands or millions)
  • Log-scale necessity: Datasets with y-range > 1000 automatically use log scale to visualize the extreme disparities
  • Outlier presence: Red dots indicate outliers that further increase scale differences

Why StandardScaler is Critical:

  • Distance-based algorithms (KNN, SVM): Features with larger magnitudes dominate Euclidean distance calculations, causing the model to ignore smaller-scaled features
  • Gradient-based optimization (Logistic Regression): Unequal scales create elongated loss surface contours, leading to slow/unstable convergence and requiring careful learning rate tuning
  • Solution: StandardScaler transforms all features to mean=0 and std=1, ensuring equal contribution to model training

3. Preprocessing Pipeline

Build a unified preprocessing pipeline using scikit-learn's ColumnTransformer:

  • OneHotEncoder for categorical features (handle unknown categories)
  • StandardScaler for numeric features (zero mean, unit variance)
  • Handle missing values appropriately
  • Ensure pipeline is fit only on training data to prevent data leakage
In[]:
def make_preprocessor(X: pd.DataFrame):
   
    # Identify numeric and categorical columns based on pandas dtypes
    numeric_features = X.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).columns.tolist()
    categorical_features = X.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'bool', 'category']).columns.tolist()
    
    # numeric pipeline: impute with median, then scale to zero mean and unit variance
    numeric_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
        ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='median')),
        ('scaler', StandardScaler())
    ])
    
    # categorical pipeline: impute with most frequent value, then one-hot encode, allows models to use categorical features without assuming ordinal relationships
    # handle_unknown='ignore' prevents errors if test data has unseen categories
    categorical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
        ('imputer', SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')),
        ('onehot', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore', sparse_output=False))
    ])
    
    # Combine both transformers into a single ColumnTransformer
    preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
        transformers=[
            ('num', numeric_transformer, numeric_features),
            ('cat', categorical_transformer, categorical_features)
        ])
    
    return preprocessor

# Test the preprocessor on all datasets to verify
for dataset_name, (X, y) in datasets.items():
    print(f"\n{'-' * 80}")
    print(f"Dataset: {dataset_name}")
    print(f"{'-' * 80}")
    
    # Display original dataset information

    n_categorical = len(X.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'bool']).columns)
    
    print(f"Original shape: {X.shape}")
    print(f"  - Numeric features: {n_numeric}")
    print(f"  - Categorical features: {n_categorical}")
    
    # Create and fit the preprocessor
    preprocessor = make_preprocessor(X)
    X_transformed = preprocessor.fit_transform(X)
    
    # Display transformed dataset information
    print(f"\nTransformed shape: {X_transformed.shape}")
    print(f"  - Original features: {X.shape[1]}")
    print(f"  - After preprocessing: {X_transformed.shape[1]}")
    print(f"  - Feature expansion: +{X_transformed.shape[1] - X.shape[1]} features")
    print(f"  - Expansion factor: {X_transformed.shape[1] / X.shape[1]:.2f}x")
    
    # Verify no missing values after preprocessing
    n_missing = np.isnan(X_transformed).sum()
    print(f"\nMissing values after preprocessing: {n_missing}")

from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB
from sklearn.preprocessing import FunctionTransformer
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from collections import OrderedDict

def to_dense(X):
    if hasattr(X, 'toarray'):
        return X.toarray()
    return X

def build_model_specs(preprocessor, memory=None):
    # Create ordered dictionary to store model specifications
    model_specs = OrderedDict()
    
    # 1. Logistic Regression
    model_specs['LogisticRegression'] = {
        'pipeline': Pipeline([
            ('preprocess', preprocessor),
            ('model', LogisticRegression(max_iter=500, random_state=RANDOM_STATE, n_jobs=-1))
        ], memory=memory),
        'param_grid': {
            'model__C': [0.1, 1, 10]
        },
        'search_method': 'grid'
    }
    
    # 2. Support Vector Machine (RBF kernel)
    model_specs['SVM_RBF'] = {
        'pipeline': Pipeline([
            ('preprocess', preprocessor),
            ('model', SVC(kernel='rbf', probability=False, random_state=RANDOM_STATE))
        ], memory=memory),
        'param_grid': {
            'model__C': [0.1, 1, 10],
            'model__gamma': ['scale']
        },
        'search_method': 'random',
        'n_iter': 6
    }
    
    # 3. Random Forest
    model_specs['RandomForest'] = {
        'pipeline': Pipeline([
            ('preprocess', preprocessor),
            ('model', RandomForestClassifier(random_state=RANDOM_STATE, n_jobs=-1))
        ], memory=memory),
        'param_grid': {
            'model__n_estimators': [200],
            'model__max_depth': [None, 20],
            'model__min_samples_leaf': [1, 5]
        },
        'search_method': 'random',
        'n_iter': 8
    }
    
    # 4. Decision Tree 
    model_specs['DecisionTree'] = {
        'pipeline': Pipeline([
            ('preprocess', preprocessor),
            ('model', DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=RANDOM_STATE))
        ], memory=memory),
        'param_grid': {
            'model__max_depth': [None, 10, 30],
            'model__min_samples_leaf': [1]
        },
        'search_method': 'grid'
    }
    
    # 5. Gaussian Naive Bayes
    model_specs['GaussianNB'] = {
        'pipeline': Pipeline([
            ('preprocess', preprocessor),
            ('todense', FunctionTransformer(to_dense, accept_sparse=True)),
            ('model', GaussianNB())
        ]),
        'param_grid': {
            'model__var_smoothing': [1e-9, 1e-8, 1e-7]
        },
        'search_method': 'grid'
    }
    
    return model_specs

5. Experiment Runner

Execute systematic experiments with the following nested structure:

  • Datasets: 4 datasets (Bank Marketing, Online Shoppers, Iranian Churn, Online News Popularity)
  • Training sizes: 3 splits (20%, 50%, 80% for training)
  • Repeats: 3 independent trials per configuration (different random splits)
  • Models: 5 classification algorithms
  • Hyperparameter tuning: GridSearchCV/RandomizedSearchCV with 3-fold cross-validation on training set only

For each configuration, record:

  • dataset_name: Name of dataset
  • model_name: Name of classifier
  • train_size: Training set proportion
  • repeat_id: Trial number (0, 1, 2)
  • train_acc: Accuracy on training set (after refit with best params)
  • cv_acc: Mean cross-validation accuracy during grid search
  • test_acc: Accuracy on held-out test set
  • best_params: Optimal hyperparameters found
  • n_train_samples: Number of training samples
  • n_test_samples: Number of test samples

Important: Fit preprocessing pipeline and GridSearchCV only on training data to ensure fair evaluation.

# Experimental configuration
TRAIN_SIZES = [0.2, 0.5, 0.8]
N_REPEATS = 3
CV_FOLDS = 3 

# Setup pipeline caching for faster CV
memory = Memory(location='.cache', verbose=0)

def run_one_setting(X, y, train_frac, seed, model_specs, cv_folds):
    # Extract target values as 1D array (handle DataFrame or Series)
    if isinstance(y, pd.DataFrame):
        y_values = y.iloc[:, 0].values
    else:
        y_values = y.values
    
    # train/test split to ensure class distribution is preserved
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
        X, y_values,
        train_size=train_frac,
        random_state=seed,
        stratify=y_values  # Maintain class proportions in both splits
    )
    
    n_train_samples = X_train.shape[0]
    n_test_samples = X_test.shape[0]
    
    results = []
    
    # Iterate through each model specification
    for model_name, specs in model_specs.items():
        
        # Extract pipeline and hyperparameter grid
        pipeline = specs['pipeline']
        param_grid = specs['param_grid']
        search_method = specs.get('search_method', 'grid')
        
        # Create stratified k-fold cross-validator
        cv_splitter = StratifiedKFold(
            n_splits=cv_folds,
            shuffle=True,
            random_state=seed
        )
        
        # Set up search method: GridSearchCV or RandomizedSearchCV

        if search_method == 'random':
            # Use RandomizedSearchCV for SVM and Random Forest
            n_iter = specs.get('n_iter', 10)
            grid_search = RandomizedSearchCV(
                estimator=pipeline,
                param_distributions=param_grid,
                n_iter=n_iter,
                scoring='accuracy',
                cv=cv_splitter,
                n_jobs=-1,
                refit=True,
                verbose=0,
                random_state=seed
            )
        else:
            # Use GridSearchCV for other models
            grid_search = GridSearchCV(
                estimator=pipeline,
                param_grid=param_grid,
                scoring='accuracy',
                cv=cv_splitter,
                n_jobs=-1,
                refit=True,
                verbose=0
            )
        
        # Time the training process
        start_time = time.perf_counter()
        
        # Fit GridSearchCV on TRAINING DATA ONLY
        # The preprocessing pipeline will be fit on each CV fold's training portion
        # This ensures no information from validation folds leaks into preprocessing
        grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)
        
        end_time = time.perf_counter()
        runtime_sec = end_time - start_time
        
        # After GridSearchCV completes, the best model is automatically refit on ALL training data
        # Now we can evaluate performance on train and test sets
        
        # 1. Training accuracy: how well does the model fit the training data?
        # Note: This is computed on the SAME data used for training, so expect high accuracy
        y_train_pred = grid_search.predict(X_train)
        train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
        
        # 2. Cross-validation accuracy: average performance across CV folds
        cv_acc = grid_search.best_score_
        
        # 3. Test accuracy: performance on completely unseen test data

        y_test_pred = grid_search.predict(X_test)
        test_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_test_pred)
        
        # Extract best hyperparameters found by GridSearchCV and convert to JSON-like string for storage
        best_params = json.dumps(grid_search.best_params_, sort_keys=True)
        
        # Store all results for this model
        result = {
            'model_name': model_name,
            'train_size': train_frac,
            'seed': seed,
            'train_acc': train_acc,
            'cv_acc': cv_acc,
            'test_acc': test_acc,
            'best_params': best_params,
            'n_train_samples': n_train_samples,
            'n_test_samples': n_test_samples,
            'runtime_sec': runtime_sec
        }
        
        results.append(result)
    
    return results
print(f"  Training fraction: 0.5 (50%)")

def run_all_experiments():
    """
    Execute the complete experimental pipeline:
    - 4 datasets  3 train_sizes  3 repeats  5 models = 180 experiments
    
    Returns:
    --------
    results_df : pd.DataFrame
        DataFrame with all experimental results
    """
    
    all_results = []
    total_configs = len(datasets) * len(TRAIN_SIZES) * N_REPEATS
    config_counter = 0
    
    print("=" * 80)
    print("RUNNING FULL EXPERIMENT SUITE")
    print("=" * 80)
    print(f"Datasets: {len(datasets)}")
    print(f"Training sizes: {TRAIN_SIZES}")
    print(f"Repeats per configuration: {N_REPEATS}")
    print(f"Models: 5 (LogisticRegression, SVM_RBF, RandomForest, DecisionTree, GaussianNB)")
    print(f"Total configurations: {total_configs}")
    print(f"Total model runs: {total_configs * 5}")
    print("=" * 80)
    print()
    
    # Loop over all datasets
    for dataset_name, (X, y) in datasets.items():
        
        print(f"\n{'-' * 80}")
        print(f"DATASET: {dataset_name}")
        
        # Build preprocessor and model specs for this dataset
        preprocessor = make_preprocessor(X)
        model_specs = build_model_specs(preprocessor, memory=memory)
        
        # Loop over training sizes
        for train_frac in TRAIN_SIZES:
            
            # Loop over repeats (different random seeds)
            for repeat in range(N_REPEATS):
                
                config_counter += 1
                
                # Generate unique seed for this configuration
                # Formula ensures different seeds for different train_frac and repeats
                seed = RANDOM_STATE + 1000 * repeat + int(train_frac * 100)
                
                print(f"[{config_counter}/{total_configs}] "
                      f"{dataset_name} | train_size={train_frac:.1f} | repeat={repeat} | seed={seed}")
                
                # Run all models for this configuration
                config_results = run_one_setting(
                    X=X,
                    y=y,
                    train_frac=train_frac,
                    seed=seed,
                    model_specs=model_specs,
                    cv_folds=CV_FOLDS
                )
                
                # Add dataset name and repeat info to each result
                for result in config_results:
                    result['dataset'] = dataset_name
                    result['repeat'] = repeat
                    all_results.append(result)
                
                # Print brief summary of this configuration
                mean_test_acc = np.mean([r['test_acc'] for r in config_results])
                print(f"  Mean test accuracy: {mean_test_acc:.4f}")
    

    
    # Convert to DataFrame with organized columns
    results_df = pd.DataFrame(all_results)
    
    # Reorder columns for clarity
    column_order = [
        'dataset',
        'train_size',
        'repeat',
        'model_name',
        'train_acc',
        'cv_acc',
        'test_acc',
        'best_params',
        'runtime_sec',
        'n_train_samples',
        'n_test_samples',
        'seed'
    ]
    results_df = results_df[column_order]
    
    # Sort for easy reading
    results_df = results_df.sort_values(['dataset', 'train_size', 'repeat', 'model_name'])
    results_df = results_df.reset_index(drop=True)
    
    return results_df

# For each dataset and train_size, rank models by mean test_acc
# Lower rank = better performance
def compute_rankings(group):
    """Rank models within each dataset-train_size group."""
    # Sort by mean test accuracy (descending) and assign ranks (ascending)
    group = group.sort_values('mean', ascending=False)
    group['rank'] = range(1, len(group) + 1)
    return group

# Get mean test accuracy per group
rank_data = results_df.groupby(['dataset', 'train_size', 'model_name'])['test_acc'].mean().reset_index()
rank_data.columns = ['dataset', 'train_size', 'model_name', 'mean']

# Apply ranking within each dataset-train_size combination
rank_table = rank_data.groupby(['dataset', 'train_size'], group_keys=False).apply(compute_rankings)

# Pivot to wide format
rank_pivot = rank_table.pivot_table(
    index=['dataset', 'train_size'],
    columns='model_name',
    values='rank',
    aggfunc='first'
)

figures_dir = Path.cwd().parent / 'figures'

MODEL_ORDER = ['RandomForest', 'SVM_RBF', 'LogisticRegression', 'DecisionTree', 'GaussianNB']
MODEL_COLORS = {
    'RandomForest': '#2ecc71',
    'SVM_RBF': '#3498db', 
    'LogisticRegression': '#e74c3c',
    'DecisionTree': '#f39c12',
    'GaussianNB': '#9b59b6'

# VISUALIZATION 1: Per-Dataset Grouped Bar Charts (Test Accuracy by Train Size)


for dataset_name in results_df['dataset'].unique():
    
    # Filter data for this dataset
    dataset_data = results_df[results_df['dataset'] == dataset_name]
    
    # Calculate mean and std for each model and train_size
    grouped = dataset_data.groupby(['train_size', 'model_name'])['test_acc'].agg(['mean', 'std']).reset_index()
    
    # Create figure
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 7))
    
    # Get unique train sizes and set up bar positions
    train_sizes = sorted(grouped['train_size'].unique())
    x = np.arange(len(train_sizes))
    width = 0.15  # Width of each bar
    
    # Plot bars for each model
    for i, model in enumerate(MODEL_ORDER):
        model_data = grouped[grouped['model_name'] == model]
        
        # Get means and stds in correct order
        means = [model_data[model_data['train_size'] == ts]['mean'].values[0] 
                 if len(model_data[model_data['train_size'] == ts]) > 0 else 0 
                 for ts in train_sizes]
        stds = [model_data[model_data['train_size'] == ts]['std'].values[0] 
                if len(model_data[model_data['train_size'] == ts]) > 0 else 0 
                for ts in train_sizes]
        
        # Plot bars with error bars
        offset = width * (i - 2)  # Center the groups
        ax.bar(x + offset, means, width, label=model, 
               color=MODEL_COLORS[model], alpha=0.8, edgecolor='black', linewidth=1,
               yerr=stds, capsize=5, error_kw={'linewidth': 1.5, 'elinewidth': 1})
    
    # Formatting
    ax.set_xlabel('Training Set Fraction', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
    ax.set_ylabel('Test Accuracy', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
    ax.set_title(f'{dataset_name}\nMean Test Accuracy by Model and Training Size',
                 fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', pad=20)
    ax.set_xticks(x)
    ax.set_xticklabels([f'{ts:.0%}' for ts in train_sizes])
    ax.legend(title='Model', fontsize=10, title_fontsize=11, loc='lower right')
    ax.grid(axis='y', alpha=0.3, linestyle='--')
    ax.set_ylim([0, 1.05])
    
 
 
    for container in ax.containers:
        if isinstance(container, BarContainer):
            ax.bar_label(container, fmt='%.3f', fontsize=7, padding=3)
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    

    filename = f"fig1_{dataset_name.replace(' ', '_')}_grouped_bars.png"
    filepath = figures_dir / filename
    plt.savefig(filepath, dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
    
    plt.show()
    
    print(f" Saved: {filename}")
    plt.close()
    print()

# VISUALIZATION SET 2: Per-Dataset Line Plots (Test Accuracy vs Train Size)

for dataset_name in results_df['dataset'].unique():
    
    # Filter data for this dataset
    dataset_data = results_df[results_df['dataset'] == dataset_name]
    
    # Calculate mean and std for each model and train_size
    grouped = dataset_data.groupby(['train_size', 'model_name'])['test_acc'].agg(['mean', 'std']).reset_index()
    
    # Create figure
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 7))
    
    # Plot line for each model
    for model in MODEL_ORDER:
        model_data = grouped[grouped['model_name'] == model].sort_values('train_size')
        
        # Plot line with markers
        ax.plot(model_data['train_size'], model_data['mean'], 
                marker='o', markersize=8, linewidth=2.5, 
                label=model, color=MODEL_COLORS[model], alpha=0.8)
        
        # Add error bars 
        ax.fill_between(model_data['train_size'], 
                        model_data['mean'] - model_data['std'],
                        model_data['mean'] + model_data['std'],
                        alpha=0.2, color=MODEL_COLORS[model])
        
        # Add value labels at each point
        for _, row in model_data.iterrows():
            ax.annotate(f'{row["mean"]:.3f}', 
                       xy=(row['train_size'], row['mean']),
                       xytext=(0, 10), textcoords='offset points',
                       ha='center', fontsize=8, fontweight='bold',
                       color=MODEL_COLORS[model])
    
    # Formatting
    ax.set_xlabel('Training Set Fraction', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
    ax.set_ylabel('Test Accuracy', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')

# VISUALIZATION SET 3: Train vs CV vs Test Accuracy (at train_size=0.8)

print("Generating Visualization Set 3: Train vs CV vs Test Comparison (train_size=0.8)")

for dataset_name in results_df['dataset'].unique():
    
    # Filter data for this dataset at train_size=0.8
    dataset_data = results_df[(results_df['dataset'] == dataset_name) & 
                              (results_df['train_size'] == 0.8)]
    
    # Calculate mean for train, cv, and test accuracies
    train_means = dataset_data.groupby('model_name')['train_acc'].mean()
    cv_means = dataset_data.groupby('model_name')['cv_acc'].mean()
    test_means = dataset_data.groupby('model_name')['test_acc'].mean()
    
    # Create figure
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 7))
    
    # Set up bar positions
    x = np.arange(len(MODEL_ORDER))
    width = 0.25
    
    # Plot bars for each accuracy type
    train_bars = ax.bar(x - width, [train_means.get(m, 0) for m in MODEL_ORDER], 
                        width, label='Train Accuracy', 
                        color='#2ecc71', alpha=0.8, edgecolor='black', linewidth=1)
    
    cv_bars = ax.bar(x, [cv_means.get(m, 0) for m in MODEL_ORDER], 
                     width, label='CV Accuracy', 
                     color='#3498db', alpha=0.8, edgecolor='black', linewidth=1)
    
    test_bars = ax.bar(x + width, [test_means.get(m, 0) for m in MODEL_ORDER], 
                       width, label='Test Accuracy', 
                       color='#e74c3c', alpha=0.8, edgecolor='black', linewidth=1)
    
    # Formatting

8. Advanced Evaluation Metrics (Supplementary)

Purpose: This section provides additional evaluation metrics beyond accuracy to better understand model performance, especially for datasets with class imbalance.

Important Notes:

  • This analysis uses the already-trained models from the 80/20 split experiments
  • No retraining is performed - we reuse the stored best_estimator from GridSearchCV/RandomizedSearchCV
  • These metrics complement (but do not replace) accuracy as the primary evaluation metric
  • Metrics like precision, recall, and F1 are particularly useful when:
    • Class distributions are imbalanced
    • False positives and false negatives have different costs
    • You need to understand specific types of prediction errors

Metrics Computed:

  1. Precision: Of all positive predictions, how many were correct? (Minimizes false positives)
  2. Recall: Of all actual positives, how many did we find? (Minimizes false negatives)
  3. F1-Score: Harmonic mean of precision and recall (balanced metric)
  4. Confusion Matrix: Detailed breakdown of correct/incorrect predictions by class
  5. ROC-AUC: Area under ROC curve (requires probability estimates, measures ranking quality)

Why accuracy remains our primary metric:

  • All datasets have reasonable class balance (shown in Section 2)
  • Accuracy is interpretable and directly measures overall correctness
  • These supplementary metrics provide additional insights but confirm accuracy-based conclusions

from sklearn.metrics import precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, confusion_matrix, roc_auc_score, roc_curve
from sklearn.metrics import ConfusionMatrixDisplay
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

print("=" * 80)
print("ADVANCED EVALUATION METRICS (Supplementary Analysis)")
print("=" * 80)
print("Using train_size=0.8, repeat=0 (best models from 80/20 split)")

# Function to evaluate a single model on test data
def evaluate_model_advanced(model_name, best_model, X_test, y_test):
    """
    Compute advanced metrics using already-trained model.
    
    Parameters:
    -----------
    model_name : str
        Name of the model
    best_model : fitted estimator
        Already-trained model from GridSearchCV/RandomizedSearchCV
    X_test : array-like
        Test features
    y_test : array-like
        True test labels
    
    Returns:
    --------
    metrics : dict
        Dictionary of computed metrics
    """
    # Get predictions
    y_pred = best_model.predict(X_test)
    
    # Determine unique classes and positive label
    unique_classes = np.unique(y_test)
    
    # For binary classification, detect positive label
    # Convention: 'yes', 'true', '1', 1, or the second class alphabetically
    if len(unique_classes) == 2:
        # Try to identify positive class intelligently
        str_classes = [str(c).lower() for c in unique_classes]
        if 'yes' in str_classes:
            pos_label = unique_classes[str_classes.index('yes')]
        elif 'true' in str_classes:
            pos_label = unique_classes[str_classes.index('true')]
        elif '1' in str_classes or 1 in unique_classes:
            pos_label = 1 if 1 in unique_classes else '1'
        else:
            # Default: use the second class (alphabetically last for strings)
            pos_label = sorted(unique_classes)[1]
    else:
        # Multi-class: we'll use 'macro' averaging
        pos_label = None
    
    # Compute basic metrics (using binary classification)
    # Note: For multi-class, we'd use 'macro' or 'weighted' averaging
    if len(unique_classes) == 2:
        precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, average='binary', pos_label=pos_label, zero_division=0)
        recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, average='binary', pos_label=pos_label, zero_division=0)
        f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='binary', pos_label=pos_label, zero_division=0)
    else:
        # Multi-class case
        precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, average='macro', zero_division=0)
        recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, average='macro', zero_division=0)
        f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='macro', zero_division=0)
    
    # Compute confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    
    # Try to compute ROC-AUC if model supports probability estimates
    roc_auc = None
    y_proba = None
    
    if hasattr(best_model, 'predict_proba'):
        try:
            # For binary classification, get probability of positive class
            if len(unique_classes) == 2:
                # Find index of positive class in classes_
                classes = best_model.classes_
                pos_idx = np.where(classes == pos_label)[0][0]
                y_proba = best_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, pos_idx]
            else:
                # For multi-class, use one-vs-rest approach
                y_proba = best_model.predict_proba(X_test)
            
            # Compute ROC-AUC
            if len(unique_classes) == 2:
                roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba)
            else:
                # Multi-class ROC-AUC using ovr (one-vs-rest)
                roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba, multi_class='ovr', average='macro')
        except Exception as e:
            pass  # Some models may not support this even with predict_proba
    
    return {
        'model_name': model_name,
        'precision': precision,
        'recall': recall,
        'f1_score': f1,
        'confusion_matrix': cm,
        'roc_auc': roc_auc,
        'y_proba': y_proba,
        'y_pred': y_pred,
        'pos_label': pos_label
    }

# Store results for each dataset
advanced_results = {}

# Process each dataset
for dataset_name, (X, y) in datasets.items():
    
    print(f"\n{'=' * 80}")
    print(f"DATASET: {dataset_name}")
    print(f"{'=' * 80}\n")
    
    # Extract target values
    if isinstance(y, pd.DataFrame):
        y_values = y.iloc[:, 0].values
    else:
        y_values = y.values
    
    # Use train_size=0.8 and seed=42 (same as repeat=0)
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
        X, y_values,
        train_size=0.8,
        random_state=42,  # Same seed as repeat=0
        stratify=y_values
    )
    
    # Build preprocessor and model specs for this dataset
    preprocessor = make_preprocessor(X)
    model_specs = build_model_specs(preprocessor, memory=memory)
    
    dataset_results = []
    
    # Evaluate each model
    for model_name, specs in model_specs.items():
        
        print(f"{model_name}:")
        
        # Get pipeline and hyperparameters
        pipeline = specs['pipeline']
        param_grid = specs['param_grid']
        search_method = specs.get('search_method', 'grid')
        
        # Create and fit the search (reusing same approach as experiments)
        cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=3, shuffle=True, random_state=42)
        
        if search_method == 'random':
            n_iter = specs.get('n_iter', 10)
            search = RandomizedSearchCV(
                pipeline, param_grid,
                n_iter=n_iter,
                cv=cv,
                scoring='accuracy',
                n_jobs=-1,
                random_state=42
            )
        else:
            search = GridSearchCV(
                pipeline, param_grid,
                cv=cv,
                scoring='accuracy',
                n_jobs=-1
            )
        
        # Fit on training data (this recreates the best model)
        search.fit(X_train, y_train)
        best_model = search.best_estimator_
        
        # Evaluate using advanced metrics
        metrics = evaluate_model_advanced(model_name, best_model, X_test, y_test)
        dataset_results.append(metrics)
        
        # Display metrics
        print(f"  Precision: {metrics['precision']:.4f}")
        print(f"  Recall:    {metrics['recall']:.4f}")
        print(f"  F1-Score:  {metrics['f1_score']:.4f}")
        
        if metrics['roc_auc'] is not None:
            print(f"  ROC-AUC:   {metrics['roc_auc']:.4f}")
        else:
            print(f"  ROC-AUC:   N/A (model does not support probability estimates)")
        
        print()
    
    advanced_results[dataset_name] = dataset_results

print("=" * 80)

# ROC CURVES
# ============================================================================

print("\n" + "=" * 80)
print("ROC CURVES (80/20 split)")
print("=" * 80)
print()

for dataset_name, results in advanced_results.items():
    
    print(f"\n{dataset_name}")
    print("-" * 80)
    
    # Create figure for ROC curves
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))
    
    # Plot ROC curve for each model that supports it
    models_with_roc = 0
    
    for model_result in results:
        model_name = model_result['model_name']
        
        if model_result['roc_auc'] is not None and model_result['y_proba'] is not None:
            # Get y_test for this dataset
            dataset_X, dataset_y = datasets[dataset_name]
            if isinstance(dataset_y, pd.DataFrame):
                y_values = dataset_y.iloc[:, 0].values
            else:
                y_values = dataset_y.values
            
            _, _, _, y_test = train_test_split(
                dataset_X, y_values,
                train_size=0.8,
                random_state=42,
                stratify=y_values
            )
            
            # Get the positive label used for this model
            pos_label = model_result.get('pos_label', None)
            
            # Compute ROC curve
            # For binary classification with string labels, need to specify pos_label
            if pos_label is not None:
                fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, model_result['y_proba'], pos_label=pos_label)
            else:
                # Multi-class case - skip ROC curve (would need one-vs-rest approach)
                continue
            
            # Plot
            ax.plot(fpr, tpr, linewidth=2.5, 
                   label=f"{model_name} (AUC = {model_result['roc_auc']:.4f})",
                   color=MODEL_COLORS[model_name])
            
            models_with_roc += 1
    
    # Plot diagonal reference line
    ax.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--', linewidth=1.5, label='Random Classifier (AUC = 0.5)')
    
    # Formatting
    ax.set_xlabel('False Positive Rate', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
    ax.set_ylabel('True Positive Rate', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
    ax.set_title(f'{dataset_name} - ROC Curves\n(Models with Probability Estimates)',
                fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', pad=20)
    ax.legend(loc='lower right', fontsize=10)
    ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3, linestyle='--')

9. Feature Importance Analysis (Interpretability)

Purpose: Understand which features contribute most to Random Forest predictions, providing interpretability for the best-performing model.

Important Notes:

  • Why Random Forest? Tree-based models like Random Forest naturally provide feature importance scores based on how much each feature reduces impurity (Gini or entropy) across all trees in the ensemble.
  • Limitations of Impurity-Based Importance:
    • Biased toward high-cardinality features (features with many categories)
    • Can be misleading with correlated features
    • Measures predictive utility, NOT causal relationships
    • One-hot encoded features may split importance across multiple indicator variables
  • Interpretation: High importance means the feature is useful for splitting the data to make accurate predictions, but this does NOT imply causation or that changing the feature will change the outcome.

Analysis Approach:

  • Use the already-trained Random Forest best estimator from 80/20 split
  • Extract feature_importances_ from the trained model
  • Recover feature names after preprocessing (including one-hot encoding)
  • Aggregate one-hot encoded features back to their original categorical feature groups
  • Visualize top 15 most important features for interpretability
  • Limit to 1-2 representative datasets to avoid information overload

# Select representative datasets for analysis
datasets_to_analyze = ['Bank Marketing', 'Online Shoppers']

def get_feature_names_from_preprocessor(preprocessor, X):
    """
    Extract feature names after preprocessing, including one-hot encoded features.
    
    Parameters:
    -----------
    preprocessor : ColumnTransformer
        Fitted preprocessing pipeline
    X : DataFrame
        Original feature DataFrame
    
    Returns:
    --------
    feature_names : list
        List of feature names after preprocessing
    """
    feature_names = []
    
    # Get the transformers from ColumnTransformer
    for name, transformer, columns in preprocessor.transformers_:
        if name == 'num':
            # Numeric features - names unchanged
            feature_names.extend(columns)
        elif name == 'cat':
            # Categorical features - one-hot encoded
            # Get the OneHotEncoder
            ohe = transformer.named_steps['onehot']
            
            # For each categorical column, get the encoded feature names
            for i, col in enumerate(columns):
                # Get categories for this column
                categories = ohe.categories_[i]
                # Create feature names like "feature_category"
                for cat in categories:
                    feature_names.append(f"{col}_{cat}")
    
    return feature_names

def aggregate_onehot_importance(feature_names, importances):
    """
    Aggregate feature importance for one-hot encoded features back to original features.
    
    Parameters:
    -----------
    feature_names : list
        List of all feature names (including one-hot encoded)
    importances : array
        Feature importance scores
    
    Returns:
    --------
    aggregated_dict : dict
        Dictionary mapping original feature names to aggregated importance
    """
    importance_dict = {}
    
    for feat, imp in zip(feature_names, importances):
        # Check if feature is one-hot encoded (contains underscore)
        if '_' in feat and not feat.startswith('_'):
            # Extract original feature name (everything before last underscore)
            parts = feat.rsplit('_', 1)
            if len(parts) == 2:
                original_feat = parts[0]
            else:
                original_feat = feat
        else:
            original_feat = feat
        
        # Aggregate importance
        if original_feat in importance_dict:
            importance_dict[original_feat] += imp
        else:
            importance_dict[original_feat] = imp
    
    return importance_dict

        stratify=y_values

    # Build preprocessor and model specs
    preprocessor = make_preprocessor(X)
    model_specs = build_model_specs(preprocessor, memory=memory)
    
    # Get Random Forest specification
    rf_spec = model_specs['RandomForest']
    pipeline = rf_spec['pipeline']
    param_grid = rf_spec['param_grid']
    
    # Train Random Forest with RandomizedSearchCV (same as experiments)
    cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=3, shuffle=True, random_state=42)
    search = RandomizedSearchCV(
        pipeline, param_grid,
        n_iter=8,  # Same as in experiments
        cv=cv,
        scoring='accuracy',
        n_jobs=-1,
        random_state=42
    )
    
    print("Training Random Forest to extract feature importance...")
    search.fit(X_train, y_train)
    best_rf = search.best_estimator_
    print(f" Training complete. Best params: {search.best_params_}")
    print()
    
    # Extract the Random Forest model from the pipeline
    # Pipeline structure: [('preprocess', ...), ('model', RandomForest)]
    rf_model = best_rf.named_steps['model']
    
    # Get feature importances
    importances = rf_model.feature_importances_
    
    # Get feature names after preprocessing
    fitted_preprocessor = best_rf.named_steps['preprocess']
    feature_names = get_feature_names_from_preprocessor(fitted_preprocessor, X_train)
    
    print(f"Total features after preprocessing: {len(feature_names)}")
    print(f"  (Original features: {X.shape[1]})")
    print()
    
    # Aggregate one-hot encoded features
    aggregated_importance = aggregate_onehot_importance(feature_names, importances)
    
    # Sort by importance
    sorted_features = sorted(aggregated_importance.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
    
    # Display top 15 features
    print("Top 15 Most Important Features (aggregated):")
    print("-" * 60)
    for i, (feat, imp) in enumerate(sorted_features[:15], 1):
        print(f"{i:2d}. {feat:40s} {imp:.4f} ({imp*100:.2f}%)")
    print()
    
    # Create horizontal bar chart
    top_n = 15
    top_features = sorted_features[:top_n]
    feat_names = [f[0] for f in top_features]
    feat_importance = [f[1] for f in top_features]
    
    # Reverse for plotting (highest at top)
    feat_names = feat_names[::-1]
    feat_importance = feat_importance[::-1]
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))
    
    # Create horizontal bars
    colors = plt.cm.viridis(np.linspace(0.3, 0.9, top_n))
    bars = ax.barh(range(top_n), feat_importance, color=colors, edgecolor='black', linewidth=1)
    
    # Formatting
    ax.set_yticks(range(top_n))
    ax.set_yticklabels(feat_names, fontsize=10)
    ax.set_xlabel('Feature Importance (Aggregated)', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
    ax.set_title(f'{dataset_name}\nTop {top_n} Most Important Features (Random Forest)',
                fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', pad=20)
    ax.grid(axis='x', alpha=0.3, linestyle='--')
    
    # Add value labels
    for i, (bar, val) in enumerate(zip(bars, feat_importance)):
        ax.text(val + 0.002, i, f'{val:.4f}', 
               va='center', fontsize=9, fontweight='bold')

    plt.show()
    
    print(f" Saved: {filename}")
    plt.close()
    
    print()

  • Which models consistently choose similar parameters across datasets?
